Gemini said
Dealing with systemd and GNU Stow can definitely feel like you're one wrong move away from a symbolic link "hall of mirrors."

The short answer: Stow the unit file, but let systemd handle the "wants."

The "loop" or mess usually happens when people try to Stow the symlinks that systemctl enable creates. You want to avoid Stowing anything inside .../target.wants/ folders.

The Recommended Strategy
Instead of trying to replicate the entire systemd folder structure, only manage the service definition itself.

Structure your dotfiles like this:

Plaintext
~/dotfiles/
└── kanata/
    └── .config/
        └── systemd/
            └── user/
                └── kanata.service  <-- The actual file
Stow it:
From your ~/dotfiles directory, run stow kanata. This creates a link from ~/.config/systemd/user/kanata.service pointing back to your dotfiles.

Enable it normally:
Run systemctl --user enable kanata.service.

Why this is the "Clean" way
When you run systemctl enable, systemd creates its own symlink in default.target.wants/.

If you Stow the "wants" folder: You’re baking a system-generated state into your dotfiles. If you ever move machines or change targets, it gets messy.

If you only Stow the .service file: You keep the "source code" of the service in your dotfiles, but let systemd manage the "activation" links. This prevents the "link-to-a-link-to-a-link" headache.

What about the "Loop of Links"?
Stow is actually pretty smart—it won't create a literal infinite loop. However, it is frowned upon to have Stow managing a symlink that points to another symlink that points to your dotfiles. It makes debugging Failed to look up unit errors a nightmare.

Pro Tip for Kanata
Since Kanata often needs root-level permissions for device I/O (but you're likely running it as a --user service), make sure your Stow'd kanata.service uses absolute paths for the binary or that the binary is in your $PATH.

Note: If you absolutely must have the service enabled automatically across all new installs via Stow, you can include the wants folder in your dotfiles, but it’s generally considered "stale" configuration.

