In the world of GNU Stow, it’s much cleaner to organize by package (the application) rather than by category (the config location).

The "Anti-Pattern" vs. The "Pro" Way
❌ The "Don't Do This" (Category-based)
~/dotfiles/systemd/
If you stow this, you're telling Stow: "I want to own the entire systemd directory." This often leads to Stow trying to manage folders like default.target.wants/ which are meant to be dynamic. It's how you end up with broken links when you uninstall something.

✅ The "Do This" (Package-based)
~/dotfiles/kanata/
You keep the Kanata service file inside the Kanata folder. This way, if you ever stop using Kanata, you just run stow -D kanata and everything—the app config and the service file—disappears at once.

How to set it up right now
If you want to keep your home directory pristine, follow this structure:

Plaintext
~/dotfiles/
└── kanata/
    └── .config/
        └── systemd/
            └── user/
                └── kanata.service
Then run:

cd ~/dotfiles

stow kanata

systemctl --user daemon-reload

systemctl --user enable --now kanata.service

Why this is better
Encapsulation: All things "Kanata" live in one place.

Safety: You aren't "owning" the ~/.config/systemd/user/ directory; you are only placing a specific file inside it.

Standardization: This follows the XDG Base Directory Specification, which systemd --user looks for by default.

