To get rid of that "bastard" without leaving a trail of broken symlinks or accidentally deleting your actual config files, you want to use the Down flag (-D).

Since Stow works based on the folder name, here is the safest play-by-play to clean the slate:

1. Unstow the old directory
Go into your dotfiles folder and tell Stow to remove the links it created for that specific package:

Bash
cd ~/dotfiles
stow -D systemd
2. The "Ghost" Check
Sometimes, if you've been moving files around manually, Stow might leave "ghost" symlinks behind if it gets confused. Quick check:

Run ls -l ~/.config/systemd/user/

If you see any red (broken) links or links pointing back to ~/dotfiles/systemd/, delete them manually with rm.

3. Move the file to the "Pro" location
Now that the old link is dead, move your service file into your existing kanata structure:

Bash
# Create the new nested directory
mkdir -p ~/dotfiles/kanata/.config/systemd/user/

# Move the service file from the old 'systemd' folder to the 'kanata' folder
mv ~/dotfiles/systemd/.config/systemd/user/kanata.service ~/dotfiles/kanata/.config/systemd/user/
4. Delete the evidence
Once you've moved the kanata.service file out of the old folder, you can safely kill the old systemd directory in your dotfiles:

Bash
rm -rf ~/dotfiles/systemd/
5. Restow and Reload
Now, tell Stow to link the new "merged" Kanata package (which now contains both your .kbd and your .service):

Bash
stow -R kanata
systemctl --user daemon-reload
Why this works:
By using stow -D, you’re telling the program: "Find every link you made based on the 'systemd' folder and snip it." This cleans up your ~/.config without you having to hunt down every individual symlink.

