Gemini said
Relative links are perfectly fine and actually the default behavior for GNU Stow.

Briefly, here is why:

Portability: If you move your entire brainy folder structure to a different drive or a different parent directory, relative links often stay "valid" as long as the internal structure remains the same.

Systemd Compatibility: systemd doesn't care if the path is relative or absolute; it just follows the link to find the text of the unit file.

Standard Stow Behavior: Stow uses relative links to avoid hardcoding your $HOME path (e.g., /home/adrian/) into the link itself, which makes syncing your dotfiles across different machines (where your username might be different) much easier.

As long as that ../../../ chain successfully reaches the file, you are golden.

